doc.ContractDescription: REMOTE SENSING OF LEAF PHYSIOLOGY RELIES ON THE FACT THAT SCATTERING FROM A LEAF RESPONDS DIFFERENTLY AT DIFFERENT WAVELENGTHS TO CHANGES IN LEAF PROPERTIES SUCH AS PIGMENT CONCENTRATIONS, CHEMICAL CONSTITUENTS AND INTERNAL STRUCTURES. LEAF SCATTERING SPECTRA, HOWEVER, CANNOT BE DIRECTLY MEASURED FROM SPACE BECAUSE THE RADIATION SCATTERED FROM LEAVES AND EXITING THE CANOPY IN THE DIRECTION OF THE SENSOR IS AFFECTED BY THE 3D CANOPY STRUCTURE AND GROUND REFLECTIVITY. MULTIANGLE DATA PROVIDE INFORMATION CRITICAL TO ACCOUNTING FOR STRUCTURAL AND GROUND CONTRIBUTIONS TO MEASUREMENTS OF LEAF OPTICAL PROPERTIES FROM REMOTE SENSING. IN ADDITION, CHARACTERISTICS OF THE LEAF SURFACE ARE ALSO IMPORTANT TO REMOTE SENSING OF LEAF PHYSIOLOGY. SOME RADIATION IS SCATTERED AT THE SURFACE OF LEAVES AND, THEREFORE, CONTAINS NO INFORMATION ON LEAF INTERIOR; THIS REPRESENTS AN ADDITIONAL CONFOUNDING FACTOR, UNLESS IT CAN BE ACCOUNTED FOR. POLARIZATION MEASUREMENTS ARE USEFUL TO QUANTIFY LEAF SURFACE CHARACTERISTICS BECAUSE RADIATION SCATTERED AT THE SURFACE OF LEAVES IS PARTLY POLARIZED WHEREAS THAT FROM THE LEAF INTERIOR IS NOT. THE LINK BETWEEN SURFACE REFLECTANCE AND LEAF LEVEL PHYSIOLOGICAL PROCESSES THEREFORE IS INDIRECT AND IS A FUNCTION OF CANOPY STRUCTURE, LEAF SURFACE PROPERTIES, LEAF OPTICS AND GROUND REFLECTIVITY. NO METHODS CURRENTLY EXIST THAT CAN RELIABLY DETECT CHANGES IN LEAF BIOCHEMISTRY FROM SATELLITE OBSERVATIONS GIVEN THAT CANOPY STRUCTURE, GROUND REFLECTIVITY, LEAF SURFACE PROPERTIES AND LEAF OPTICS EXHIBIT STRONG NATURAL VARIABILITY. THE OBJECTIVE OF THE PROPOSED RESEARCH IS TO DEVELOP A SOLID THEORETICAL BASIS FOR RETRIEVING LEAF BIOCHEMICAL CONSTITUENTS, CANOPY GEOMETRIC STRUCTURES, FOLIAGE SURFACE CHARACTERISTICS, BACKGROUND REFLECTANCE FROM SYNERGISTIC ANALYSES OF HYPERSPECTRAL, MULTIANGULAR AND POLARIMETRIC DATA WITH AN EMPHASIS ON QUANTIFYING THE ASSOCIATED ERRORS AND UNCERTAINTIES. THE BASIC CONCEPT OF THE PROPOSED APPROACH WAS ORIGINALLY DEVELOPED IN REACTOR PHYSICS TO QUANTIFY THE CRITICALITY CONDITION. IT PROVIDES A POWERFUL MEANS TO PARAMETERIZE CANOPY STRUCTURE AND SCATTERING PROCESS ACROSS MULTIPLE SCALES IN TERMS OF VARIABLES THAT THREE DIMENSIONAL 3D RADIATIVE TRANSFER EQUATION RTE NATURALLY ADMITS. THE 3D RTE PROVIDES THE MOST PHYSICALLY CONSISTENT LINKAGE BETWEEN REMOTE SENSING DATA AND CANOPY STRUCTURAL AND BIOPHYSICAL VARIABLES AND THUS WILL UNDERLIE OUR APPROACH TO ASSESS AND QUANTIFY IMPACTS OF CANOPY HETEROGENEITY, LEAF SURFACE AND OPTICAL PROPERTIES ON THE RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN CANOPY REFLECTANCE AND LEAF BIOCHEMICAL CONSTITUENTS. THIS METHODOLOGY WILL BE USED TO CORRECT HYPERSPECTRAL DATA FOR EFFECTS OF CANOPY HETEROGENEITY; RELATE CORRECTED DATA TO PROPERTIES OF LEAF SURFACES, LEAF OPTICS AND LEAF BIOCHEMISTRY; AND QUANTIFY ERRORS AND UNCERTAINTIES IN THE SYNERGISTIC APPROACH TO MONITOR 3D CANOPY STRUCTURE AND LEAF LEVEL PHYSIOLOGICAL PROCESSES. THE DATA SET FOR DEVELOPING AND VALIDATION OF THE PROPOSED APPROACH INCLUDES EXISTING GROUND DATA ON LEAF OPTICS AND CANOPY STRUCTURE AND SIMULTANEOUSLY AVAILABLE DATA FROM NASA S AIRBORNE MULTIANGLE SPECTROPOLARIMETRIC IMAGER AIRMSPI AND AIRBORNE VISIBLE INFRARED IMAGING SPECTROMETER AVIRIS.

doc.ContractDescription: IN ORDER TO UNDERSTAND HOW THE CLIMATE RESPONDS TO VARIATIONS IN FORCING, ONE NECESSARY COMPONENT IS TO UNDERSTAND THE FULL DISTRIBUTION OF VARIABILITY OF EXCHANGES OF HEAT AND MOISTURE BETWEEN THE ATMOSPHERE AND OCEAN. A NUMBER OF STUDIES RECOGNIZE THE IMPORTANT ROLE OF SURFACE HEAT AND MOISTURE FLUXES IN THE GENERATION AND DECAY OF IMPORTANT COUPLED AIR SEA PHENOMENA. THESE MECHANISMS OPERATE ACROSS A NUMBER OF SCALES AND CONTAIN SIGNIFICANT CONTRIBUTIONS FROM INTERACTIONS BETWEEN THE ANOMALOUS NON MEAN, OFTEN EXTREME VALUED, FLUX COMPONENTS. IT IS IMPORTANT TO HAVE A CHARACTERIZATION AND UNDERSTANDING OF THESE PROCESSES FOR THE DEVELOPMENT OF ACCURATE MODELING EFFORTS. WE PROPOSE A UNIFIED APPROACH TO EVALUATE THE REPRESENTATION OF THE TURBULENT FLUXES AT THE AIR SEA INTERFACE IN THE CURRENT AND EVOLVING GODDARD EARTH OBSERVING SYSTEM GEOS MODEL. ONE ASPECT OF THIS PROPOSAL WILL BE THE EVALUATION OF THE EXTENT TO WHICH THE DISTRIBUTIONS OF THE FLUXES IN THE OBSERVATIONAL DATA AND THE NASA GEOS 5 AND WHEN AVAILABLE GEOS 6 MODELS DIFFER WITH DIFFERING WEATHER AND CLIMATE STATES, AND EXPLORE THE DRIVING OCEANIC AND ATMOSPHERIC FACTORS PRODUCING THE DISTRIBUTIONS. WE WILL EVALUATE HOW THE DISTRIBUTIONS OF THE FLUXES VARY IN SPACE AND TIME BETWEEN THESE DATASETS, THEIR REPRESENTATION IN DIFFERENT WEATHER REGIMES, AND HOW THESE VARIATIONS AFFECT THE CLIMATOLOGY. PARTICULAR EMPHASIS IS PLACED ON UNDERSTANDING THE DISTRIBUTION OF THE FLUXES INCLUDING EXTREMES, AND THE REPRESENTATION OF NEAR SURFACE FORCING VARIABLES DIRECTLY RELATED TO THEIR ESTIMATION. THE EXTENT TO WHICH THE MODEL SIMULATIONS OF THE SURFACE FLUXES RECTIFY ONTO SEA SURFACE TEMPERATURE ON SEASONAL TO INTERANNUAL TIME SCALES WILL BE QUANTIFIED. THE PROPOSED INCLUSION OF DIURNAL SEA SURFACE TEMPERATURE WARMING, WAVE EFFECTS, AND SURFACE ROUGHNESS CHANGES IN GEOS 6 ESTABLISHES A NEED TO CHARACTERIZE THEIR IMPACTS TO THE REPRESENTATION OF TURBULENT SURFACE HEAT AND MOISTURE FLUXES. PRIMARILY, THIS WORK ADDRESSES THE MAPPING, ANALYSIS, AND PREDICTION MAP PROGRAMMATIC PRIORITY OF CHARACTERIZING THE LIMITS OF VALIDITY OF MODELS AND MODEL COMPONENTS AND IDENTIFYING THE SOURCES OF UNCERTAINTIES. TURBULENT LATENT AND SENSIBLE HEAT FLUXES ARE KEY VARIABLES IN THE ESTIMATION OF EARTHS ENERGY AND WATER CYCLES. IN GEOS 6 THE AIR SEA INTERFACE WILL BE THE FOCUS OF MUCH OF THE OCEAN WORK, AND OUR ANALYSIS OF THE CURRENT AND EVOLVING GEOS MODELS WILL PROVIDE CONTEXT FOR THE EXTENT TO WHICH NEW MODEL PARAMETERIZATIONS ARE IMPROVING THE PHYSICAL REPRESENTATION OF THIS CRUCIAL BOUNDARY. THIS RESEARCH ADDRESSES THE TASK OF USING OBSERVATIONS TO IDENTIFY AND CHARACTERIZE MODEL UNCERTAINTIES IN KEY ASPECTS OF THE AIR SEA COUPLING ON SYNOPTIC TO INTERANNUAL TIME SCALES. THE ANTICIPATED RESULTS OF THIS RESEARCH WILL BE THREE-FOLD BETTER UNDERSTANDING OF THE DISTRIBUTION OF SURFACE FLUXES ACROSS THE GLOBAL OCEANS, KEY FEEDBACKS AND REGIMES THAT NEED FURTHER IMPROVEMENTS IN THE MODELS, AND TRACEABILITY OF IMPROVED AIR SEA FLUX PARAMETERIZATIONS AND BOUNDARY MODELS AND THEIR EFFECTS IN GEOS 5 AND 6 MODELS.
